VLast January, my company, Fark.com, was sued
p4
aValong with Yahoo, MSN, Reddit,
p5
aVAOL, TechCrunch and others
p6
aVby a company called Gooseberry Natural Resources.
p7
aVGooseberry owned a patent
p8
aVfor the creation and distribution
p9
aVof news releases via email.
p10
aV(Laughter)
p11
aVNow it may seem kind of strange that such a thing can actually be patented,
p12
aVbut it does happen all the time.
p13
aa(lp14
VTake something already being done
p15
aVand patent it for an emerging technology \u2014
p16
aVlike phone calls on the internet
p17
aVor video listings for TV shows
p18
aVor radio but for cellphones,
p19
aVand so on.
p20
aVThe problem with these patents
p21
aVis that the mechanisms are obscure
p22
aVand the patent system is dysfunctional,
p23
aVand as a result, most of these lawsuits end in settlements.
p24
aVAnd because these settlements are under a non-disclosure agreement,
p25
aVno one knows what the terms were.
p26
aVAnd as a result, the patent troll can claim
p27
aVthat they won the case.
p28
aa(lp29
VIn the case of Gooseberry Natural Resources,
p30
aVthis patent on emailing news releases
p31
aVhad sort of a fatal flaw
p32
aVas it pertained to myself,
p33
aVand that was that in the mainstream media world
p34
aVthere is only one definition for news release,
p35
aVand it turns out that is press release \u2014
p36
aVas in P.R.
p37
aVNow my company, Fark,
p38
aVdeals with news, ostensibly,
p39
aVand as a result
p40
aVwe were not in violation of this patent.
p41
aVSo case closed, right?
p42
aVWrong.
p43
aa(lp44
VOne of the major problems with patent law is that,
p45
aVin the case that when you are sued by a patent troll,
p46
aVthe burden of proof that you did not infringe on the patent
p47
aVis actually on the defendant,
p48
aVwhich means you have to prove
p49
aVthat you do not infringe on the patent they're suing you on.
p50
aVAnd this can take quite a while.
p51
aVYou need to know that the average patent troll defense
p52
aVcosts two million dollars
p53
aVand takes 18 months when you win.
p54
aVThat is your best case outcome
p55
aVwhen you get sued by a patent troll.
p56
aa(lp57
VNow I had hoped to team up with some of these larger companies
p58
aVin order to defend against this lawsuit,
p59
aVbut one-by-one they settled out of the case,
p60
aVeven though \u2014 and this is important \u2014
p61
aVnone of these companies
p62
aVinfringed on this patent \u2014 not a one of them.
p63
aVAnd they started settling out.
p64
aVThe reason they settled out
p65
aVis because it's cheaper to settle than to fight the lawsuit \u2014
p66
aVclearly, two million dollars cheaper in some cases,
p67
aVand much worse if you actually lose.
p68
aVIt would also constitute a massive distraction for management of a company,
p69
aVespecially a small eight-man shop like my company.
p70
aa(lp71
VSix months into the lawsuit,
p72
aVwe finally reached the discovery phase.
p73
aVAnd in discovery phase,
p74
aVwe asked the patent troll to please provide
p75
aVscreenshots of Fark
p76
aVwhere the infringement of their patent
p77
aVwas actually occurring.
p78
aVNow perhaps it's because no such screenshots actually existed,
p79
aVbut suddenly Gooseberry wanted to settle.
p80
aVTheir attorney:
p81
aV"Ah, yes. My company's having a reorganization on our end."
p82
aVNever mind the fact
p83
aVthat the address led to a strip mall somewhere in Northern L.A.
p84
aVwith no employees.
p85
aV"And we'd like to go ahead and close this out.
p86
aVSo would you mind giving us your best and final offer?"
p87
aVMy response:
p88
aV"How about nothing?!"
p89
aV(Applause)
