aa(lp105
VNow what did I learn from this case? Well, three things.
p106
aVFirst of all, if you can,
p107
aVdon't fight the patent, fight the infringement.
p108
aVPatents are very difficult to overturn.
p109
aVInfringement is a lot easier to disprove.
p110
aVSecondly, make it clear from the beginning
p111
aVthat either you have no money at all
p112
aVor that you would rather spend money with your attorney fighting the troll
p113
aVthan actually giving them the money.
p114
aVNow the reason this works
p115
aVis because patent trolls
p116
aVare paid a percentage of what they're able to recover in settlements.
p117
aVIf it becomes clear to them that they cannot recover any money,
p118
aVthey become less interested in pursuing the case.
p119
aa(lp120
VFinally, make sure that you can tell them
p121
aVthat you will make this process
p122
aVas annoying and as painful
p123
aVand as difficult as possible for them.
p124
aVNow this is a tactic that patent trolls are supposed to use on people
p125
aVto get their way.
p126
aVIt turns out, because they're paid on contingency,
p127
aVit works really, really well in reverse.
p128
aVDon't forget that.
p129
aa(lp130
VSo what does all this mean?
p131
aVWell to sum up,
p132
aVit boils down to one thing:
p133
aVDon't negotiate with terrorists.
p134
aV(Applause)
p135
aVPatent trolls have done more damage to the United States economy
p136
aVthan any domestic or foreign
p137
aVterrorist organization in history
p138
aVevery year.
p139
aVAnd what do they do with that money?
p140
aVThey plow it right back into filing more troll lawsuits.
p141
